{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 MK Slicer\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a lua script for quick slicing, quantizing by grid, re-quantizing, triggering or sampling audio.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Key features:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Advanced detector. Thanks to filters and good visualization, you can precisely cut even material in which transients are not initially visualized.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Quick Slicing or placing Markers (by Transients or by Grid).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One click Quantize by Grid. Without gaps, clicks and artificial duplication of items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Ability to work with multitracks. Slices and quantizes your multitrack drums phase-accurate, quickly and without pain. Items in the multitrack will be automatically grouped.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Re-Quantizing. When quantizing with a grid larger than the step of the transients, you can re-quantize your loops to get unique material.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One click sampling and exporting into RS5k.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Trigger. Easy conversion of rhythmic parts to midi patterns with accurate velocity reproduction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Random - a function for randomizing slices and some of their parameters. Ideal for uniqualization, humanization and creation of new parts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Pitch detection: the ability to convert simple single-voiced parts and drums to midi.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Tempo detection, item rate change to adapt to project tempo. Ability to create a tempo map from an item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adaptive initial settings. Upon initialization, the script sets the View Gain, Threshold, and Retrig settings depending on the material and tempo of the project.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Instructions for use:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Select an item or several items. If items on multiple tracks are selected, only the top one will be analyzed. If several items are selected on the same track, they will be glued together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Run the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Do your work.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab To cancel an actions, use Reset or just Ctrl + Z. Reset sliders to default: Ctrl + Click. Fine tune: Shift + Drag. Exit the script: Esc, Space - Play.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On Waveform Area: Mouswheel or Left/Right keys - Horizontal Zoom, Ctrl(Shift)+Mouswheel or Up/Down keys - Vertical Zoom, Left or Middle Drag - Move View (Horizontal Scroll), Left Click - Set Edit Cursor, Left Drag Small Flag - Move Marker, Ctrl+Left Drag - Change Velocity, Right Click on Marker - Delete Marker, Right Click on Empty Space - Insert Marker.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Working with multitrack:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 0.\tx360\tab Before starting the work, I recommend you to create a guide track - usually a mixdown kick, snare and toms tracks together in one track. This track will be used as a \u8220"lead\u8221" for the detector to operate more accurately After the work is completed, you can delete it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Select items. If items on multiple tracks are selected, only the top one will be analyzed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Run the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Do your work. When a slicing or placing markers occurs on a multitrack, items will be automatically added to Groups.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Important.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For the machanism Reset to operate correctly and for the operations on-the-fly to follow each other smoothly, it is OBLIGATORY for the items to start from the beginning of the bar. It's the condition which ensures comfortable work without surprises like a sudden move of the items after the following quantization. Additionaly, I don't recommend to change selection manually or do anything with the items while the script is working. Also, do not forget to save your project regularly. Just in case.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Sometimes a script applies glue to items. For example, when several items are selected and when a MIDI is created in a sampler mode.\par}
}

