{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script copies/moves all notes and/or CC events to user specified MIDI channels. If in the target MIDI channel there're already events for a particular CC message\line or the piano roll already contains notes, these will be replaced by those being copied or moved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Run the script\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab In the 1st input field list target MIDI channel numbers space separated or specify range as X - X (inverted range is supported, e.g. 13 - 4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab In the 2nd and/or 3d input fields enter letter M or m if you wish the events to be moved or any other character if you want them copied\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Click OK\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Besides strictly CC events also supported are Pitch bend, Program change and Channel pressure events.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 CAVEATS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To be aware that Bezier curve in Pitch bend envelope may very slightly change in the target MIDI channel after copying/moving. However this is not a consistent behavior. https://forum.cockos.com/showthread.php?t=273173\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script copies/moves selected notes and/or selected CC events in visible lanes to user specified MIDI channels. If the target lane in another MIDI channel already contains events or piano roll already contains notes, these will be replaced by those being copied or moved.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If several CC lanes are open, selected events in 14 bit CC lanes will be ignored, therefore if you need them affected by the sctipt be sure to switch 14-bit lanes to their 7-bit counterparts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Select MIDI notes and/or other MIDI events\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Run the script\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab In the input field list target MIDI channel numbers space separated or specify range as X - X\line (inverted range is supported, e.g. 13 - 4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Precede the list/range with the letter M or m if you wish the events to be moved rather than copied\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Click OK\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there're several visible lanes and only one of them contains selected events be sure to make it the last clicked by clicking it so that the events are\line copied/moved to the lane of the same message type in other MIDI channels.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Besides strictly CC events also supported are Pitch bend, Program change and Channel pressure events.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Meant as an alternative to the default note insert action which inserts a note at the velocity of the last selected note with no way to define a constant velocity to which each new note will be set.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For proper functionality the script depends on 'Exclusive dummy toggles (12 scripts)' script set which can be installed via ReaPack as well.\line Velocity of a note inserted with this script is conditoned on the ON toggle state of one of such exclusive dummy toggle scripts.\line For setup refer to the USER SETTINGS below.\line If 'Exclusive dummy toggles (12 scripts)' set isn't installed this script defaults to velocity value of 100.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the script uses 'Edit: Insert note at mouse cursor' action, it obeys Grid if 'Snap to grid' option is enabled.\line Since a note is inserted at mouse cursor, strictly speaking clicking isn't necessary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However if assigned to 'double click' context at Preferences -> MIDI Editor piano roll, and you don't want the cursor to move when a note is inserted (default behavior) then make sure that in the parallel slot or one with at least one same modifier under the 'left click' context there's no action (behavior) which moves the edit cursor, otherwise the first click out of the two will change the edit cursor position.\line If this can't be ensured, then run it independently of the mouse click, that is via a shortcut assigned to the script in the Action list.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 SCREENSHOT:\line https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Buy-One/screenshots/main/Insert%20note%20at%20constant%20velocity%20depending%20on%20dummy%20toggle%20scripts.gif\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script behavior can be replicated with an SWS Cycle action which executes MIDI Editor custom actions depending on the state of dummy toggle scripts. As a blueprint for such custom actions the following code can be used (you can import it into the MIDI Editor section of the Action list as a .ReaperKeyMap file):\line ACT 3 32060 "26f61be727877d41933795baf400dadf" "Custom: Insert note at velocity 100 -- scalable" 40214 40001 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40464 40659\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Create as many such custom actions as velocity presets you need by modifying this blueprint custom action to produce the required velocity value and then in the MIDI Editor section of the Cycle action editor construct a Cycle action as follows:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 IF If next action is ON\line Script: BuyOne_Exclusive dummy toggle 1.lua\line Custom: Insert note at velocity A\line ENDIF End of conditional statement\line IF If next action is ON\line Script: BuyOne_Exclusive dummy toggle 2.lua\line Custom: Insert note at velocity B\line ENDIF End of conditional statement\line IF If next action is ON\line Script: BuyOne_Exclusive dummy toggle 3.lua\line Custom: Insert note at velocity C\line ENDIF End of conditional statement\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 and so on repeating the IF - ENDIF block as many times as needed.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 GUIDE\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Meant as an alternative to the native {\i 'Edit: Insert note at mouse cursor'} action which inserts a note at the velocity of the last selected note or at the velocity set by clicking on the Piano roll graphic keyboard with no way to define a constant velocity to which each new note will be set.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script is basically the same as the following custom action:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ACT 3 32060 "26f61be727877d41933795baf400dadf" "Custom: Insert note at velocity 100 (assign to double click in MIDI piano roll mouse modifiers) -- scalable" 40214 40001 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40465 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40463 40464\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 but with extra features.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unlike with left drag, the length of inserted note is dictated by the setting in the {\i 'Notes:'} menu at the bottom of the Piano roll so it equals to the length of current grid division.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the note is inserted at mouse cursor strictly speaking clicking isn't required.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However if assigned to 'double click' context at {\i 'Preferences -> Mouse modifiers -> MIDI Editor piano roll'}, and you don't want the cursor to move when a note is inserted (default behavior) then make sure that in the parallel slot or one with at least one same modifier under the 'left click' context there's no action (Behavior) which moves the edit cursor, otherwise the first click out of the two will change the edit cursor position.\line If this can't be ensured, then run it independently of the mouse click, that is via a shortcut assigned to the sctript in the Action list.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u9619? \u9642? INITIAL VELOCITY\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Initial velocity to which notes inserted with this script will be set to is controlled by the user modifiable INIT_VELOCITY parameter in the USER SETTINGS below. It is constant until changed via the dialogue.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u9619? \u9642? DIALOGUE\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In order to set velocity for all new notes to anything other than INIT_VELOCITY, move the mouse cursor away from the Piano roll (e.g. place it above Piano roll graphic keyboard or the main toolbar or the bottom part) and run the script. In the dialogue which will pop up key in the new velocity value and click 'OK'. In order to reset the operational velocity back to the INIT_VELOCITY value enter 0 in the dialogue field.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The velocity value set via the dialogue is stored in the project file. If the project file wasn't saved after using the dialogue, in the next session the script will start out with INIT_VELOCITY.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u9619? \u9642? MODIFIER\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can set selected notes to the new velocity specified in the dialogue by adding any alphabetic character after the velocity value. Select notes before calling the dialogue as it blocks the UI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the dialogue is called from inside a floating MIDI Editor window, the window will lose focus and will have to be put back into it with a mouse click. Until then the script won't run if called with a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script isn't designed to work with MIDI Inline editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u9619? \u9642? IGNORE_MARGINS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This setting prevents REAPER action 'Edit: Insert note at mouse cursor', which is used in this script, from inserting a note when the mouse cursor is outside of the active Piano roll area on the left (excluding the graphic keyboard) or right (essentially outside of the item bounds) because it may trigger the dialogue when it's uncalled for.\line This comes at a small price of the edit cursor slightly jolting every time a note is inserted in the active Piano roll area and inability to extend the item by inserting a note outside of its bounds while 'Loop item source' option is OFF.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If you find edit cursor jerks annoying you can disable this setting but then try to avoid running the script when the mouse cursor is outside of the active Paino roll area on the left (excluding the graphic keyboard) or right.\par}
}

