{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inserts CCs between selected "nodes" in the CC lane under the mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for smoothing transitions between CCs that were drawn at low resolution.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for converting a set of nodes into an LFO with any desired curve shape.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MODES: WARP and B\u203?ZIER:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script offers two modes (selected by right-clicking the mouse):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Warp: The user can the shape of the connecting ramps by moving the mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab B\u233?zier: The script tries to find the smoothest curve to connect all selected nodes. Moving the mouse does not affect the curve.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE MOVEMENT AND WARPING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Warp mode resembles the "js_Mouse editing - Warp" script, except that the Warp script would warp all ramps and all selected events together, whereas this script warps each ramp individually, without changing the position of values of the nodes. Moving the mouse left and right warps each individual ramp horizontally, and moving up and down warps each ramp vertically. All kinds of shapes can be created, from straight lines to "fast start", "fast end", and sine (aka "slow start / slow end".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE BUTTONS:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Left button: Terminates the script. Middle button: In Warp mode, switches between linear/power curves and sine-based curves. Right button: Switches between modes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSEWHEEL AND MIDI CHANNELS:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The mousewheel changes the channel of the inserted MIDI events.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the MIDI editor is set to "Edit only the active MIDI channel", the script will only select nodes that are in the active channel. These channel features are very useful for keeping the ramps and the nodes in separate channels, so that the nodes can easily be re-selected and edited.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 OTHER NOTES:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The "Connect nodes" script is often used directly after the "Extract nodes" script, and these can usefully be combined in a single custom action, so that both can be run with a single shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts works in inline MIDI editors as well as main MIDI editors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab New CCs will be inserted at the MIDI editor's default density that is set in Preferences -> CC density.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Any extraneous CCs between selected events will deleted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC), if the control script "js_Option - Toggle skip redundant events when inserting CCs" is toggled on.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select the "node" CCs between which ramps will be inserted.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse over the target CC lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Press the shortcut key. (Do not press any mouse button.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab Move the mouse or mousewheel to shape the ramps.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 5)\tx360\tab To stop the script, left-click, or press any key, or if the shortcut key has been held down for more than half a second, simply release the key.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key (Ctrl/Cmnd, Alt, Shift or Win) while theh script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and edit takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of edit and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Draw various basic LFO shapes in real time (without chasing start values).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Includes: Triangle, Saw, Sine, Cosine and Square, as well as plain straight line and parabola.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The mousewheel scrolls through the various LFO shapes. (The script will remember the last-used shape.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If snap to grid is enabled in the MIDI editor, the endpoints of the LFO will snap to grid, allowing precise positioning of the LFO.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script inserts new CCs, instead of only editing existing CCs. (CCs are inserted at the density set in Preferences -> MIDI editor -> "Events per quarter note when drawing in CC lanes".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC), if the script "js_Option - Skip redundant events when inserting CCs" is toggled ON.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "js_Mouse editing" scripts can be controlled by the mouse while the script is running: * Left click: Terminates the script. * Middle click: -- (Usually switces between a sine and linear/power curve, but not used by this script) * Right click: Toggles between chasing start values and using the mouse original position as start value. * Mousewheel: Scrolls through the available LFO curves. * Any keystroke: Terminates the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIPS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Draw linear, curved or sine ramps of MIDI CCs and automation envelopes events in real time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Works in automation envelopes as well as inline MIDI editors and full MIDI editors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script was conceived before REAPER v6 introduced CC envelopes, and was intended as a workaround to quickly draw smooth ramps. Now that REAPER has native CC envelopes, the script is largely deprecated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab SNAP TO GRID: If snap to grid is enabled in the MIDI editor, the endpoints of the ramp will snap to grid, allowing precise positioning of the ramp (allowing, for example, the insertion of a pitch riser at the exact position of a note).\line Holding down Shift will override snap-to-grid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab CHASING START VALUES: Right-clicking toggles between chasing existing CC values at the line start position, and starting at the mouse's original vertical position. Chasing ensures that CC values change smoothly. In the USER AREA, the user can customize whether chasing should interpolate envelope segments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab LINEAR OR SINE SHAPES: Clicking the middle button toggles between a linear shape and a sine shape, which can be tweaked into other shapes such as parabolic.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab TWEAK THE CURVE: By using the mousewheel, the shape of the ramp can be tweaked. Linear ramps can be smoothly morphed to parabolic, for example.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab SKIP REDUNDANT CCs: This script (like all other js_ scripts that insert new CCs) can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC). This is controlled by the script "js_Option - Toggle skip redundant events when inserting CCs".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab ZOOM-DEPENDENT RESOLUTION: CCs and envelope points are inserted at a maximum density set in Preferences -> MIDI editor -> "Events per quarter note when drawing in CC lanes". Since REAPER v6 now has CC envelopes, a high CC density is not necessary for smooth ramps any more, so in the USER AREA, the user can customize whether the resolution should be zoom dependent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The events in the newly inserted ramp are automatically selected and other events in the same lane are deselected, which allows immediate further shaping of the ramp (using, for example, the warping or arching scripts).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As already mentioned above, the script can be controlled by the mouse while the script is running: * Left click: Terminates the script. * Middle click: Toggles the ramp shape between 1) linear/power curve and 2) sine ("slow start / slow end") curve. * Right click: Toggles between 1) chasing start values and 2) no chasing, use original mouse position. * Mousewheel: Tweaks the ramp curve. (NB: The longer the mousewheel is kept moving, the faster the curve will change. The curve will also momentarily pause when it reaches the default, middle value.) * Any keystroke: Terminates the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 STARTING AT MINIMUM OR MAXIMUM\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In order to start a ramp at the minimum or maximum value, the starting position of the mouse can be slightly outside the target lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the case of MIDI, the mouse can be positioned over a CC lane divider.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the case of automation envelopes, the selected envelope takes precedence (whether take or track): If the mouse starting position is close to the selected envelope, the selected envelope will be edited, even if the starting position was inside another lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key (except Shift) while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
