{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A multifunctional script for stretching, scaling, tilting and warping of MIDI and automation envelopes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script is intended to work similar to REAPER's native left-drag mouse modifier functions -- but with more advanced functionality:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, recall how to run REAPER's native mouse modifier functions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * You press the modifiers key(s) and then hold them down while left-clicking or left-dragging the mouse.\line
\line
* The effect of a mouse modifier function often depends on the starting position of the mouse:\line
    For example, Alt+left-dragging from the right edge of a note stretches the note, \line
    whereas Alt+left-dragging from the inside of a note changes velocity.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Similarly, to run this script, you press the shortcut key (instead of the modifier key), then click or drag the mouse from specific starting positions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Beyond these basic similarities, however, this script offers several advanced features:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * The various positions from which the mouse can be clicked or dragged are displayed onscreen as colored zones.\line
\line
* The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, \line
  using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\line
\line
* Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button,\line
  the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\line
\line
* Multiple editing steps can be performed before terminating the script, and the precise (floating point) positions and values of the events\line
    are remembered between steps, to avoid rounding errors when rounding to the nearest tick positions or 128-step values ranges. \line
\line
* And, of course, the script offers a variety of editing tools such as warping, compressing, stretching and tilting that are not found among REAPER's native actions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 EDITABLE ITEMS:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If using an up-to-date version REAPER (v6.37 or newer), the script will edit selected MIDI events in all editable items, if either of the following options is enabled:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Options: Draw and edit CC events on all tracks\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Options: Edit CC events on all tracks\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If using an older version of REAPER (v6.36 or older), the script can only edit selected MIDI events in all editable items if the following options are enabled (in addition to the ones mentioned in the previous paragraph):\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Preferences -> MIDI editor -> One MIDI editor per project\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Options: MIDI track list/media item lane selection is linked to editability\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If these setting are not all enabled, the script will only edit events in the active item.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 LANE UNDER MOUSE vs MULTIPLE LANES:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the case of MIDI, the script can either affect 1) all selected MIDI events, or 2) only the selected MIDI events in lane under the mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * To edit only the selected events in a single lane, the mouse must be positioned inside that lane when the script starts.  \line
    (After the script has started, the mouse may move out of the starting lane.)\line
\line
* To edit all selected events together, the mouse must be positioned over a lane divider, or over the ruler -- i.e., outside any lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When editing all selected events, only their tick positions can be edited, using the warp, stretch or reverse functions.\line When editing a single lane, positions as well as values can be edited.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the case of track automation -- but not take envelopes -- the script can edit multiple envelope lanes together, if either * a razor selection has been made across multiple lanes, or * automation items have been selected in multiple lanes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are multiple ways to select track automation envelopes, and the order of precedence is razors > AIs > points: * If any razor selections are active, these will override any AI selections and point selections. * If no razor selections are active, all points within selected AIs will be edited. * If no razor areas and no AIs are selected, only selected points in the envelope lane under the mouse will be edited.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: This script regards razor selections as simply another way of selecting points. Unlike automation items, each razor selection is not a separate envelope.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 STARTING THE SCRIPT:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  (NOTE: To run the script, the shortcut key can either be held down for as long as the script must run, similar to REAPER's native mouse modifier functions,\line
          or the shortcut key can be clicked once to start the scripts and then once again the terminate the script.) \line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ZONES AND FUNCTIONS:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As soon as the shortcut key is pressed, colored zones will light up on screens, indicating the available functions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each zone may either be left-click/dragged, mousewheel-triggered, or right-clicked. The zones and their associated left-button / mousewheel functions are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Compress lane from top / Flip values absolute\line
* Compress lane from bottom / Flip values absolute\line
* Scale values from top / Flip values relative\line
* Scale value from bottom / Flip values relative\line
* Warp left/right or up/down (depending on initial mouse movement) / Reset and evenly space events\line
* Stretch from left / Reverse positions\line
* Stretch from right / Reverse positions\line
* Tilt left side / Snap to chased values on left\line
* Tilt right side / Snap to chased values on right\line
* Move up/down and left/right / Flip values absolute\line
* Undo\line
* Redo      \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note that left-clicking and left-dragging can both be used to run the same functions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To proceed to next step:\line * If the mouse was dragged, proceed by lifting the mouse button.\line * If the mouse button was clicked, proceed by clicking a second time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Right-clicking on a zone while the zones are displayed pops up a context menu through which zone color and zone size can be customized, and tooltips can be toggled on/off.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TWEAKING WHILE RUNNING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The scripts' functioning can be tweaked while the script is running:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Middle-clicking switches the curve shape:  \line
      In the case of compression and tilting, it switches between sine (aka slow start/end) and power (aka linear, slow start, and slow end) curves.\line
      In the case of warping, it switches between slow start and slow end warp shapes.\line
\line
* Mousewheel tweaks the steepness of the curves.\line
  NOTE: The longer the mousewheel movement, the faster the curve is changed.  The curve can therefore be changed from a central position to extreme with a single mousewheel sweep. \line
        When sweeping from one extreme to the other, the curve will temporarily pause at the central position.  It is therefore easy to return the curve to the central position.\line
\line
* Right-clicking switches between one-sided mode and two-sided / symmetrical mode.\line
\line
* If the Shift key is held down while stretcing, snapping is ignored.  \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TERMINATE THE SCRIPT:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To terminate the script:\line * If the shortcut key was held down, terminate by lifting the key.\line * If the shortcut key was clicked and released, terminate by pressing any key (excluding some special keys such as Shift). * Clicking or mousewheel outside any zone (when the mouse cursor is a cross).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script allows multiple "Mouse editing" scripts to be run from a single (keyboard or mousewheel) shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The shortcut that is linked to this script will toggle start/stop any "Mouse editing" script that is armed in the toolbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TOOLBAR ARMING\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of "Mouse editing" scripts depends on initial mouse position (similar to REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), these scripts cannot be run by mouse-clicking a toolbar button or the Actions list.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative, scripted, solution for toolbar arming:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run the script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel (or both) shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 (In other words, the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each Mouse editing script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Select events in the MIDI editor's CC lanes by simply swiping the mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 All events within the horizontal (time) range of mouse movement will be selected, and the mouse does not need to touch the CC bars.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned over a CC lane when the script starts, only events in that lane will be selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the mouse is positioned over a CC lane divider when the script starts, events in all visible lanes will be selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the the mouse is not position over the MIDI editor piano roll, the script will arm itself, so that it can be called via the script "js_Run the 'Mouse editing' script that is selected in toolbar (link this to shortcut and mousewheel)".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSE EDITING SCRIPTS vs REAPER's LEFT-DRAG MOUSE MODIFIER ACTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" script resemble REAPER's own left-drag mouse modifier actions (such as "Draw CCs", "Arpeggiate", "Paint notes", etc), in that the scripts follow mouse movement and continue to run until the user stops the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the scripts are more advanced than the native actions:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scripts' functioning (such as the ramp shape or the channel of inserted CCs) can be tweaked while the script is running, using the mousewheel, mouse middle button and right button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whereas native actions can only be started and stopped by left-dragging and lifting the mouse button, the scripts be started and stopped in multiple ways, allowing a more customized and streamlined workflow.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Starting a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 * Similar to any action in the Actions list, the script can be assigned a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\line
  To start and stop the script using a shortcut, you have two options: \line
      1) Two keystrokes: To start, press the shortcut key once *without holding the key down* and then press the same or any other key to stop;\line
      2) Press and hold: Press the shortcut key and hold it down for as long as the script should run. If the key is held down for more than one second, the script will terminate when the key is released.\line
\line
* Similar to mouse modifier actions, assign the script to a left-click or double-click mouse modifier in Preferences -> Mouse modifiers.  \line
  (NOTE: In current versions of REAPER, actions can not be assigned to left-drag mouse modifiers, \line
         but the script will automatically detect a left-drag movement. To use left-drag, assign the script to a *double*-click mouse modifier.)\line
\line
* Arming a toolbar button, as described below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Stopping a script:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left clicking while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse: Left-dragging and lifting the left button after holding the button down for more than one second.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Pressing any key while the script is running.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Keyboard: Releasing the shortcut key after holding it down for more than one second.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 RUNNING THE SCRIPT FROM THE TOOLBAR:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the functioning of the script depends on initial mouse position (similar to some of REAPER's own mouse modifier actions, or actions such as "Insert note at mouse cursor"), the script cannot be run from a toolbar button.\line This problem is solved by "arming" toolbar buttons for delayed execution after moving the mouse into position:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER's NATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 REAPER natively provides a "toolbar arming" feature: right-click a toolbar button to arm its linked action (the button will light up with an alternative color), and then left-click to run the action after moving the mouse into position over the piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two niggles with this feature, though:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Left-drag is very sensitive: If the mouse is even slightly moved while left-clicking, the left-drag mouse modifier action will be run instead of the armed toolbar action;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Multiple clicks: The user has to right-click the toolbar (or press Esc) to disarm the toolbar and use left-click normally again, then right-click the toolbar again to use the script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ALTERNATIVE TOOLBAR ARMING:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The "js_Mouse editing" scripts therefore offer an alternative "toolbar arming" solution:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Link the "js_Mouse editing - Run script that is armed in toolbar" script to a keyboard or mousewheel shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Link the individual Mouse editing scripts (such as "Draw ramp", "Warp", etc) to toolbar buttons. (No need to link them each to a shortcut.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  (I.e. the Run script is linked to a shortcut, while the individual Mouse editing scripts are linked to toolbar buttons.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab If the mouse is positioned over a toolbar or over the Actions list when the Mouse editing script starts (or, actually, anywhere else outside the MIDI piano roll and CC lanes), the script will arm itself and its button will light up with the normal "activated" color.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab When the "Run" script is executed with its shortcut, it will run the armed Mouse editing script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By using this feature, each "Mouse editing" script does need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "Run" script needs to be linked to a shortcut.\par}
