{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As far as going to send destination track is concerned the script is an alternative to the native feature accessible in the TCP/MCP send slot right click menu. It lists all send destinations in a single menu along with their basic information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In addition the script provides a facility to go to receive source tracks which isn't available natively.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The menu lists send destination / receive source track index, name (if any), number of sends/receives routed from/to the given track, whether send destination / receive source track is a child in a collapsed folder (-c) and whether it's hidden in the currently active context (-h) which is either the Arrange view or the Mixer.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The currently active context is determined by the Mixer visibility. If visible the target track will be scrolled to in the Mixer, otherwise it will be scrolled to in the Arrange view.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When the script is run via a shortcut, it displays sends/receives menu of a track under mouse cursor. A click on the send or receive menu item makes the tracklist scroll to the corresponding track and select it. In the Mixer such track ends up at the leftmost position, in the Arrange view - in the middle of the tracklist.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the send destination / receive source track happens to be inside a collapsed folder in the Mixer, its parent or the leftmost visible grandparent track of a collapsed folder its parent is a child in (if any) is scrolled into view instead.\line If the track is visible in the Mixer and happens to be in a collapsed folder whose parent track is hidden, the leftmost visible grandparent track of a collapsed folder its parent is a child in (if any) is scrolled into view.\line The send destination / receive source track is selected even if its (grand)parents are scrolled into view, so in case it's inside a collapsed folder it's easy to pick it out after uncollapsing the folder.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there's no track under mouse cursor the script looks for the first selected track. Thus it can also be run from a toolbar or a menu in which case the relevant track must be selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If there're more than one send to or receive from a particular track, the total of such sends/receives is displayed in square brackets next to the destination track entry in the menu. This if purely for information.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To close the menu without action click elsewhere with the mouse or click 'Esc' key on the keyboard or click 'close' menu item at the bottom.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script allows saving track template with selected items or items within time selection provided option\line 'Include track items in template'\line is enabled in 'Save track template' dialogue. REAPER native action saves all items on selected tracks. Without the option enabled the script is useless.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Inspired by a feature request at\line https://forum.cockos.com/showthread.php?t=277300\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script works in 2 stages, first it triggers the native action 'Track: Save tracks as track template...' to allow you to save track template as normal.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once 'Save track template' dialogue is closed the script immediately triggers custom 'Select .RTrackTemplate file' dialogue inviting you to select the template just saved in order to process it.\line After the newly saved template is selected and button 'Open' is clicked in the dialogue the script completes its task leaving the track template only containing items you selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 'Select .RTrackTemplate file' dialogue points to the /TrackTemplates folder inside REAPER resource directory which is the default location for saving track templates.\line If you saved a template elsewhere, simply navigate to that location.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 G I U D E\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script in essense does in its own way what the native Track Manager, the SWS extension Find utility, mpl_search tracks.lua, X-Raym_Scroll vertically to track by name and select it.lua, spk77_Track Tags.lua, tack_Select Track By Name.lua, Lokasenna_Select tracks by name.lua scripts do. In addition, besides track names track indices can be used to get to them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 OPERATORS (the character case is irrelevant)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Search term modifiers: e, c, i\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 no operator - Search track by elements contained in the track name\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 e - (exact) Search by exact name; the operator covers syntax, scope of the track name and the register of its characters, so to satisfy the search the track name must only consist of the search term and match its characters register; without this operator any track name which contains all the elements of the search term regardless of their order will be valid (see above)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 c - (case) Ignore search term and track name register; can be enabled permanently in the USER SETTINGS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 i - (index) Search track by index, the search term is interpreted as track index hence only numerals are supported; ignored when the search term is a mix of alphabetic and numeric characters; if along with numerals the search term contains alphabetic and/or punctuation characters 'i' operator is ignored; combined with the exclusive display mode 'h' operator (see below) this operator supports lists and ranges in the format: (for range) 1-5=ih or 5-1=ih, and (for list) 1,3,5=ih, in this case if the search term containing a single numeral is followed by a comma the operator will work; 'i' operator can be enabled permanently in the USER SETTINGS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Action operators: u, h, s\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 u - (uncollapse) Uncollapse all collapsed parent tracks if the matching track is inside a collapsed folder, including nested; doesn't apply to MCP, where if track is inside collapsed folders its first uncollapsed parent track is the one to be scrolled into view; can be enabled permanently in the USER SETTINGS as well as a setting to restore collapsed state of folders at the end of the search if their children tracks matched the search term but were skipped\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 h - (hide) Hide all tracks bar those whose name/index matches the search term, and if such track belongs to a folder then bar all its parents, children and siblings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 s - (show) Unhide all tracks hidden through the use of exclusive display mode 'h' operator; this operator should not be preceded by '=' sign (see below) but feature alone in the search field; to make the script ignore 's' character as an operatior and allow searching for 's' or 'S' characters in track names add '=' sign after them\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Examples:\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If applied, operators must follow the search term and be separated from it with the '=' sign, they can be combined, e.g.:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ad-lib - scroll to a track whose name contains the word 'ad-lib';\line background vox - scroll to a track whose name contains both words regardless of their order or presence of intervening elements;\line 10 - scroll to a track whose name contains numeral '10';\line 10=i - scroll to track No 10;\line bass=ec - scroll to a track named exactly 'bass', disregarding the name's register (case), so the name 'BASS' is also valid;\line guitar=u - scroll to a track whose name contains the word 'guitar' and if it's a child in a collapsed folder, uncollapse it;\line 12,35,44=hiu - exclusively show tracks No 12, 35 and 44 (including their folder relatives, if any) and if any of them is a child in a collapsed folder, uncollapse it;\line DRUMS=ch - exclusively show tracks whose names contain the word 'DRUMS' (including their folder relatives, if any), disregarding the word's register (case) so names containing 'drums' are also valid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The order in which the operators are combined and their register is immaterial.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the TCP context (Arrange) the searched track is scrolled into view at the top of the tracklist. In the MCP context it's scrolled to the leftmost position. Contexts are enabled in the USER SETTINGS.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the searched track is inside a collapsed folder and 'u' operator isn't used, then its first uncollapsed parent track is scrolled into view.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the found track is a folder child track, the track which ends up being selected depends on the currently active context, TCP or MCP, because folder state which the selection is conditioned by, in TCP and MCP may differ. If both contexts are active, track selection in the TCP has priority. Since track selection is global it cannot be different between the TCP and the MCP at the same time, so TCP has been chosen to be primary.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If several track names match the search term, after the 1st one found is scrolled into view the input dialogue reappears to allow continuing the search for the next one. When the last such track has been found the search dialogue doesn't reappear.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Unless 'e' (exact) operator is used all elements of a multi-word search term must be present in a track name regardless of their order.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 EXCLUSIVE DISPLAY MODE\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 'h' operator allows to selectively show tracks whose index or names match the search term and the criteria set by the operators while keeping the rest hidden. To selectively show tracks by their indices make sure to add 'i' operator to the 'h' operator, i.e. 'ih' or 'hi'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When only TCP or MCP context is enabled in the USER SETTINGS only tracks in this context will be hidden and unhidden.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When tracks matching the search term are part of a folder, the entire folder they belong to is shown, except for the tracks hidden prior to the application of the 'h' operator.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When exclusive display mode is first activated the tracks matching the search term do not scroll into view.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When tracks are in exclusive display mode the search dialogue search field is autofilled with 'h' perator showing that the mode is active. To be able to search tracks while in exclusive display mode remove the 'h' operator from the search field.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To unhide all tracks hidden through the use of the 'h' run 's' operator alone.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whether sends or receives are affected is determined by the user settings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can be duplicated and each copy dedicated to work either with sends or receives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The next mode is relative to the current mode of each given send/receive, therefore if several sends/receives are initially set to different modes their resulting modes will differ as well\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sets selected tracks sends or receives to the same mode selected with an interactive dialogue\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whether send or receives are affected is determined by the user settings\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can be duplicated and each copy dedicated to work either with sends or receives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Or TYPE_DIALOGUE option can be enabled to allow manual selection of the target type (sends or receives)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When TYPE_DIALOGUE option is enabled TYPE option value can be whatever, just not empty\par}
