}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script is designed for duplication of objects according to the active context determined by a mouse click.\line So before using the script you can click any track, Arrange canvas or envelope or their elements to activate required context.\line Still the script provides an option to select context with a context switch key inside the input box.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The native 'Nudge/set items' utility allows duplicating media items but doesn't affect tracks or automation items, so this sctipt attempts to coalesce duplication tasks in one place.\line It also allows free (within music theory limits) formatting of note lengths. The advantage of 'Nudge/set items' utility in this respect is that items can be selected when the utility is open. The script input box however blocks the UI so selection must be done beforehand and can't be changed without closing the box.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 CAVEATS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The action 'Options: Trim content behind automation items when editing or writing automation' doesn't affect automation items when pasting, therefore after duplication of automation items some of them may end up overlapped and occupy different lanes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Further details see in HELP below or run the script, type in h in the upper field and click OK.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 GUIDE\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script is designed to allow using REAPER menus independently of REAPER menu system by loading .ReaperMenu files on demand, which essentially allows potentially having and using many more menus and toolbars than the REAPER native menu system provides.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The dynamic part implies that a currently loaded menu can at any moment be replaced with another one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab .ReaperMenu files are menu and toolbar dumps which can be created with {\i Export -> Export current menu/toolbar to ReaperMenu file...} option in the {\i Customize menus/toolbars} section accessible from the main {\i Options} menu in the default REAPER installation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab So when you need another menu/toolbar but have used up all menus/toolbars available in REAPER natively, you can create a backup copy of one of the current menus/toolbars, put together a new one in its place, export the newly created menu/toolbar to a .ReaperMenu file, then restore the previous one and use such exported menu/toolbar via this script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Toolbars loaded with this script are formatted as regular menus.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In the USER SETTINGS below the script provides options to specify the full path to the .ReaperMenu file per supported section of the Action list.\line If such path isn't specified the script will offer loading a file and then will store its full path so it can be loaded automatically on next runs until another menu file is loaded.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A menu item titled 'LOAD REAPER MENU FILE' is found at the very bottom of any menu loaded via the dialogue. So if your menu is long you may need to scroll all the way down to access it. Scrolling can be done with the up/down arrow keys on the keyboard while the mouse cursor is placed over the menu.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The default directory which the load dialogue is pointed to is \\MenuSets in the REAPER resource directory, the one to which REAPER offers to save its .ReaperMenu files by default. But the file can be browsed to and loaded from elsewhere.\line The file path specified in the USER SETTINGS may point to a .ReaperMenu file located anywhere on the hard drive.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab When the full path to the .ReaperMenu file is specified in the USER SETTINGS below, the load dialogue menu item is inactive because if you load another file, on the next run the script will still default to the file located at the path specified in the USER SETTINGS.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The same script can be added to and run from 3 sections of the Action list: {\i Main}, {\i MIDI Editor} and {\i MIDI Event List Editor} and maintain different menus.\line The sections {\i Main} and {\i Main (alt recording)} share the same content, therefore the script added to the {\i Main} section in the {\i Main (alt recording)} section will have the same menu.\line If this script has been installed via ReaPack application it has been automaticaly added to both {\i Main} and {\i MIDI Editor} sections of the Action list.\line Besides that, multiple instances of the script can be created under slightly different names, loaded into any or all 3.5 mentioned sections of the Action list and used with different .ReaperMenu files in parallel.\line If you prefer specifying the path to the menu file in the USER SETTINGS below use the option proper for the section of the Action list the script is going to be run from.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Actions in {\i Media Explorer} section of the Action list cannot be launched with this script and using it from {\i MIDI Inline Editor} section is impractical therefore it has been made incompatible with them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can run MIDI Editor menus from Arrange even if the MIDI Editor is closed.\line If you do so while working with the MIDI Inline Editor be aware that the grid and snap settings which will be used by the menu actions (such as Split and the like) are those of the main MIDI Editor unless option {\i Use the same grid division in arrange view and MIDI editor} is enabled in the Snap/Grid settings.\line If MIDI Editor is closed toggle state indicators (if any) won't appear next to the menu items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Likewise Arrange menus can be run from inside the MIDI Editor.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This set of 10 scripts borrows the concept of SWS extension 'SWS/S&M: Dummy toggle' actions but makes dummy toggle exclusive within the scope of an Action list section, meaning that when one of 10 scripts toggle state is ON, toggle state of the rest 9 is OFF while the state of a given script in one Action list section is completely independent from its state in other Acton list sections.\line These can be useful in switching between options/modes of operation depending on the state of a specific dummy toggle script, for example with the SWS Cycle actions through conditional statements or within other scripts. One such use case is switching between velocity presets in the MIDI Editor, another - mouse tool switcher. The switching can be done from a toolbar or a menu via toolbar buttons or menu items linked to the dummy toggle scripts.\line You can expand the script set by duplicating any instance, giving its duplicate a unique number and importing it into every Action list section.\line With the USER SETTINGS the script set can be divided into subsets (groups) so that every script in a subset only affects toggle state of other scripts in this subset. This way each subset can be dedicated to a specific task which requires mutually exclusive modes.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 2 independent scripts designed to facilitate sharing one REAPER installation between several users.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However the concept can be applied to using the same REAPER installation for different purposes which would likely entail different workflows and thus different setup requirements.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Technically it's achieved by copying files storing REAPER settings from REAPER resource directory to a separate folder homonymous with the profile and which is located under {\i \\ProfileTerminalData} directory in REAPER resource directory, and then copying them back to the REAPER resource directory when profile is being loaded.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Designed for either horizontal scrolling or moving loop or time selection by the custom increments set in the USER SETTINGS either in seconds or in musical intervals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Both functions can be combined so that loop and/or time selection are kept in view during scrolling.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Besides the incerement defined in the USER SETTINGS, the script provides for an ad-hoc interval which overrides that setting for the duration of the REAPER session or until changed or cleared.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab To call an ad-hoc interval creation dialogue move the mouse cursor to the upper left hand corner of your screen on Windows (bottom left hand corner on MacOS) (whether REAPER program window is fully open or not) and execute the script.\line In the dialogue type in the new interval value in format explained\line in the annotation to the INCREMENT setting of the USER SETTINGS, and click 'OK'.\line In the dialogue type in the new interval value in format explained\line in the annotation to the INCREMENT setting of the USER SETTINGS, and click 'OK'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab To clear an ad-hoc interval to be able to return to using the one defined in the INCREMENT setting, type in x or X and click 'OK'.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Be aware that scrolling distance is not 100% precise because it's measured in pixels and conversion from time units such as seconds and musical intervals to pixels is always an approximation, but it's within the ballpark. The greater the zoom-in the more accurate the scrolling.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use effectively bind the script to the mousewheel.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u9658? M u s i c a l i n t e r v a l s s y n t a x\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Syntax of supported straight and triplet musical intervals:\line 1/256, 1/192, 1/128, 1/96, 1/64, 1/48, 1/36, 1/24, 1/16, 1/12, 1/8, 1/6, 1/4, 1/3, 1/2, 1, 2 etc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The fraction numerator can be greater than 1, e.g. 10/16, 5/12, and greater than the denominator, which is useful when an interval longer than 1 whole note is required, e.g.\line 3/2 is 1.5 notes, 5/2 is 2.5 notes, 4/3 is 1 + 1/3 notes (a whole + 1/2 triplet), 5/3 is 1 + 2/3 notes (a whole + two 1/2 triplets).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Length of a dotted note is equivalent to the length of 3 notes of a shorter duration, e.g. 1 dotted = 3/2, 1/2 dotted = 3/4, 1/4 dotted = 3/8 etc. To combine several dotted notes multiply the nominator by the number of such notes, e.g. 9/2 = 3 dotted whole notes (3 x 3/2), 12/4 = 4 dotted half notes (4 x 3/4), 6/8 = 2 dotted quarter notes (2 x 3/8).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Appending dotted notes to whole notes:\line 1 whole note + 1/2 dotted = 4/4 + 3/4 = 7/4, 2 whole notes + three 1/16 dotted = 64/32 + 3 x 3/32 = 64/32 + 9/32 = 73/32.\par}
}

